Sure, here are some example sentences in Serbian that use the word "pasa" in different forms and positions:

1. Moj pas *pasa* sa drugim psima u parku. (My dog plays with other dogs in the park.)
2. Kada sam se vratila kući, pas je već spavao *pasaći* na svom jastuku. (When I came home, the dog was already sleeping curled up on his pillow.)
3. Da li ćeš dati psu da *pasa* kost? (Will you give the dog a bone to chew on?)
4. Naš pas *pasu* jako voli da trči po livadi. (Our dog loves to run around the meadow.)
5. Pas je odjednom počeo *pasaći* oko stola kada smo počeli da jedemo. (The dog suddenly started circling around the table when we started eating.)
6. Za psa nije bilo mesta u avionu, pa smo ga morali *pasačiti* u prtljažniku automobila. (There was no room for the dog on the plane, so we had to transport him in the car trunk.)
7. Prošli put kada smo išli u šetnju, pas je *pasačio* na svakom drvetu. (Last time we went for a walk, the dog marked his territory on every tree.)
8. Naš pas *pasu* jako voli da se igra loptom. (Our dog loves to play with a ball.)

Translations in English are provided in parentheses after each sentence.